            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "@untitaker I know you've already heard this, but adding my comments so they are on the record and up for discussion.\n\nThere is some good stuff to follow as per the pytest [good practices](http://pytest.org/latest/goodpractises.html):\n\n>    make sure that \u201cmypkg\u201d is importable, for example by typing once\n\nThe general practice, at least for me, when using `py.test` is to run:\n\n```\n$ pip install -e .\n```\n\nTo setup the environment properly for `py.test`. Then I can run:\n\n```\n$ py.test tests\n```\n\n> avoid \u201c**init**.py\u201d files in your test directories. This way your tests can run easily against an installed version of mypkg, independently from the installed package if it contains the tests or not.\n\nThe `tests` folder shouldn't be treated as a package. `py.test` will run the tests in the context of the `tests` folder, making the `tests` the current working directory. \n"
        },
